article.headline: Arizona State 65, California 64 (2 OTs)
article.story: BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) -- With two big men fouled out and a third banged up, Arizona State coach Rob Evans didn't want to take his chances with a third overtime. So with his team trailing by two in the final seconds, he told point guard Antwi Angounou to penetrate and find either Bryson Krueger or Kevin Kruger for a 3-pointer. Bryson Krueger hit the 3 from the corner with 10.5 seconds left to lead Arizona State to a 65-64 victory Saturday night and deny California a chance to take sole possession of first place in the Pac-10. "They're both really good 3-point shooters," Evans said. "It didn't matter which one shot it as long as one of them got a really good look at it. It's got a 50-50 chance of going in if they shoot it. Fortunately for us it was the right 50." It looked as if Cal (16-7, 10-4) had taken control in the second overtime when Ayinde Ubaka ended a nearly 8-minute stretch without a field goal with a basket with 2:26 remaining. He then fed DeVon Hardin for a dunk on the next possession, making it 64-60. With Jeff Pendergraph and Craig Austin fouled out and Serge Angounou on the bench with an injured knee, the Sun Devils (10-14, 4-11) battled back. Kevin Kruger scored to cut it to two with 1:01 left and Powe missed two free throws -- his only misses in 15 trips to the line -- to give last-place Arizona State the chance. "That's the intensity level you have to bring into each game and we were lacking that for whatever reason," Kevin Kruger said. "We weren't scared going into tonight, not at all. We accepted the challenge of playing the top team in the Pac-10 at their place." Ubaka missed on Cal's final possession, giving the Sun Devils the win. The last-place Sun Devils outhustled the Golden Bears for loose balls and made the big shots when they needed them to get the upset. This marked the second time this season that Cal lost at home the game after moving into first place. After starting 3-0, the Bears lost last month to Oregon State. They vowed to avoid a similar letdown this time, but fell short and had their six-game winning streak snapped. "Our team obviously is down after the game. I don't know how you can play that game and not be down," Cal coach Ben Braun said. "We have to come back. That's our challenge right now. We have to bounce back. We can't go back to this game. It's over. We have to have the same mentality we had during that stretch. That's going to be our challenge right now." Cal's players declined to talk to the media after the game. Bryson Krueger scored 19 points, Kevin Kruger had 16, Pendergraph had 15 points and 11 rebounds for the Sun Devils, who lost by 30 points at home last month to Cal. Arizona State outrebounded Cal 41-31, including 16 offensive rebounds. Braun had made defensive rebounding a priority, making this game particularly frustrating. "That's just disappointing because we had opportunities," Braun said. "We have to learn from this game. This is kind of a rerun in the rebounding department. To me it's one of the bigger indicators we have." Powe, who was slowed by flu-like symptoms, led the Bears with 23 points and 10 rebounds, but only took 11 shots from the field as the Sun Devils tried their best to deny him the ball. "We really worked on him," Evans said. "We really tried to front him. We tried to make him work hard to get the basketball. I thought we did a good job on him. We just couldn't keep him off the free-throw line." The game was close the entire first overtime, with Bryson Krueger's drive giving the Sun Devils a 58-57 lead with 1:15 remaining. Freshman Theo Robertson made one of two free throws with 1 second remaining to send the game into a second overtime. Trailing by two late in regulation, Ubaka drove for the tying score with 22.7 seconds left -- Cal's last basket until midway through the second overtime. Ubaka finished with 12 points. Hardin had 13 points and 10 rebounds. The Bears were coming off perhaps their best performance of the season, a 75-66 victory over Arizona on Thursday in which they shot 58 percent. They weren't nearly as efficient against the Sun Devils, turning the ball over 15 times and shooting just 39 percent. After brothers Jordan and Omar Wilkes hit consecutive 3-pointers midway through the half to give Cal a 22-10 lead, the Bears didn't make another field goal for more than 9½ minutes. Powe got a three-point play off an offensive rebound with 2.9 seconds left to give Cal a 27-21 lead at the break.
